Sure, these days I see a lot of foreigners using chopsticks better than native Japanese.

72
00:06:02,920 --> 00:06:09,400
So, Dr. Takahashi, as a former colleague of Tenma's, what would you say was your impression of him?

73
00:06:09,920 --> 00:06:11,460
Let's see...

74
00:06:11,460 --> 00:06:19,900
Well, as I remember, he wasn't a hard guy to like, though he was occasionally more than a bit indecisive.

75
00:06:20,900 --> 00:06:21,480
Still...

76
00:06:21,480 --> 00:06:22,260
Go on.

77
00:06:22,760 --> 00:06:25,520
With a scalpel in his hand, he was a whole other person.

78
00:06:27,740 --> 00:06:33,180
People called him a genius brain surgeon, and I can say that was no exaggeration.

79
00:06:33,980 --> 00:06:35,240
What about his parents?

80
00:06:35,860 --> 00:06:39,140
Hmm. He never really talked about his parents much.

81
00:06:39,380 --> 00:06:42,560
But he said his father and older brother were doctors also,

82
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:46,820
so I guess they put him on the physician's path whether he liked it or not.

83
00:06:48,580 --> 00:06:54,960
In fact, I think I remember him saying he hadn't been back to Japan since coming to Germany for medical school.

84
00:06:56,440 --> 00:07:00,940
In fact, his parents didn't come to Germany at all to support him when the scandal broke.

85
00:07:01,360 --> 00:07:04,580
I don't think they made any public appeal for their son's innocence either.

86
00:07:05,200 --> 00:07:08,040
I guess he and his family weren't all that tight-knit.

87
00:07:08,480 --> 00:07:09,120
You know what I mean?

88
00:07:21,500 --> 00:07:22,580
Thanks for waiting.

89
00:07:22,580 --> 00:07:26,440
Sorry it's taken so long, but we've just gotten word from Yamamoto.

90
00:07:27,060 --> 00:07:28,900
He's left Prague and is back in Munich,

91
00:07:29,140 --> 00:07:33,500
