Look at me look at me

166
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:05,940
The monster inside me has gotten this big I

167
00:12:08,940 --> 00:12:12,600
See so Johan is pulling the strings on that billionaire

168
00:12:12,600 --> 00:12:17,840
Dr. Gillen, you've been telling me all about this Johan person for a while now.

169
00:12:18,520 --> 00:12:20,980
You've painted him as quite the monster, haven't you?

170
00:12:22,220 --> 00:12:23,080
Monster, eh?

171
00:12:23,720 --> 00:12:27,120
Well, yeah. I mean, I've killed some people, sure.

172
00:12:27,920 --> 00:12:31,980
But he's transformed himself into the sort of creature I could only dream of becoming.

173
00:12:32,640 --> 00:12:35,320
This Johan has become my idol, my hero.

174
00:12:35,840 --> 00:12:40,860
Really? Well, there is one more question that I would like to ask of you, if you don't mind.

175
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:41,980
Knock yourself out.

176
00:12:42,600 --> 00:12:45,340
Poor Johan, what would be the next move that you made?

177
00:12:45,780 --> 00:12:46,100
Next?

178
00:12:47,320 --> 00:12:49,280
Well, that's obvious.

179
00:12:50,640 --> 00:12:52,800
The parents, you know, the Lieberts.

180
00:12:53,500 --> 00:12:55,600
I think it would be time for them to die.

181
00:12:57,640 --> 00:12:58,920
Uh, Mr. Liebert?

182
00:13:02,440 --> 00:13:03,520
Mr. Liebert!

183
00:13:04,220 --> 00:13:06,140
What brought you to that conclusion?

184
00:13:07,280 --> 00:13:07,840
Because...

185
00:13:07,840 --> 00:13:09,280
I've gotten bored.

186
00:13:09,600 --> 00:13:11,580
Mr. Liebert, open up this door!

187
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:12,920
Mrs. Liebert!

188
00:13:15,800 --> 00:13:16,860
Yes, hello.

189
00:13:20,920 --> 00:13:24,580
You're a psychologist? I'm sorry, we don't understand.

190
00:13:24,980 --> 00:13:27,040
What can we do for you, Dr. Reichwein?

191
00:13:27,220 --> 00:13:29,680
I won't waste your time with a long-winded explanation.

192
00:13:30,140 --> 00:13:33,320
I just want to ask some questions about your adopted son, Johan.

193
00:13:34,820 --> 00:13:35,740
Johan? Adopted?

194
00:13:36,180 --> 00:13:40,680
You must be mistaken. That boy is our child. I gave birth to him and I--

195
00:13:40,680 --> 00:13:41,760
That's enough, Mrs. Liebert.

196
00:13:42,600 --> 00:13:45,520
for a fact that your real child is buried in Bruntal.

197
00:13:46,680 --> 00:13:49,160
There was a fire that burned down the town hall

198
00:13:49,160 --> 00:13:50,660
along with all the birth records.

199
00:13:50,900 --> 00:13:53,480
The fire allowed you to apply for a new birth certificate

200
00:13:53,480 --> 00:13:55,920
as if your original child were still alive.

201
00:13:58,000 --> 00:13:59,320
- What's this all about?

202
00:13:59,880 --> 00:14:02,420
- Look, I didn't come here to make threats, I promise you.

203
00:14:02,800 --> 00:14:04,840
All I want to do is help if you'll let me.

204
00:14:05,600 --> 00:14:07,040
Please, read this.

205
00:14:08,460 --> 00:14:10,580
It's a report about Johan.

206
00:14:10,580 --> 00:14:13,040
About Johan?

207
00:14:13,380 --> 00:14:16,200
Yes. A friend compiled that information.

208
00:14:17,960 --> 00:14:18,340
Oh!

209
00:14:21,560 --> 00:14:26,000
I've met him. He came to the house selling insurance policies.

210
00:14:26,860 --> 00:14:29,960
That man was former detective Richard Brown.

211
00:14:30,440 --> 00:14:31,400
He's a detective?

212
00:14:32,080 --> 00:14:34,540
He was. He's dead now.

213
00:14:36,540 --> 00:14:37,560
Just read.

214
00:14:38,180 --> 00:14:40,700
The story actually starts a few years ago,

215
00:14:40,940 --> 00:14:43,660
when an East German government official escaped

216
00:14:43,660 --> 00:14:46,580
and sought refuge here in West Germany in 1986.

217
00:14:47,160 --> 00:14:49,020
What's it about? Is he after money?

218
00:14:49,320 --> 00:14:52,320
Money? Nah, Johann couldn't care less about money.

219
00:14:52,760 --> 00:14:56,160
Then why go after a billionaire like Schuwald in the first place?

220
00:14:57,480 --> 00:14:59,640
You know that thing you did as a kid?

221
00:14:59,920 --> 00:15:00,540
What thing?

222
00:15:01,280 --> 00:15:03,900
When I was a kid, I would find a line of ants.

223
00:15:04,540 --> 00:15:08,300
Yeah, and then I'd play with 'em. Mess with their formation.

224
00:15:16,600 --> 00:15:17,720
My God.

225
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:21,340
I refuse to believe this. It's all simply dreadful.

226
00:15:21,740 --> 00:15:23,180
This story's ridiculous.

227
00:15:24,300 --> 00:15:27,060
Look, I understand that you don't want to believe it.

228
00:15:27,220 --> 00:15:30,260
The two of you lost your only son at a very early age.

229
00:15:30,500 --> 00:15:34,220
I know. Your life moves on and you wait to be blessed with a new child

230
00:15:34,540 --> 00:15:37,580
until one day a boy nearly the same age as yours appears.

231
00:15:37,760 --> 00:15:40,120
And to sweeten the pot, the boy arrives with money.

232
00:15:40,940 --> 00:15:43,540
He provides you with a wonderful house to live in,

233
00:15:43,740 --> 00:15:46,500
in a nice neighborhood, with a beautiful garden.

234
00:15:47,600 --> 00:15:49,540
And he provides you with love.

235
00:15:51,740 --> 00:15:54,700
I understand that both of you want to believe in him.

236
00:15:55,040 --> 00:15:56,680
However, everything that's written

237
00:15:56,680 --> 00:15:58,440
in these documents is true.

238
00:15:59,180 --> 00:16:01,180
So who is Johan, really?

239
00:16:02,380 --> 00:16:04,920
I need you to tell me about Yohan!

240
00:16:10,280 --> 00:16:12,540
Yohan is a good boy.

241
00:16:13,220 --> 00:16:15,400
Yes, he's just a very nice boy.

242
00:16:16,080 --> 00:16:17,800
And he's very smart.

243
00:16:18,060 --> 00:16:19,100
A clever boy.

244
00:16:19,380 --> 00:16:22,680
You see, Yohan is our reason for being.

245
00:16:25,760 --> 00:16:27,220
And is that all?

246
00:16:28,200 --> 00:16:31,380
You've been acting as his parents for years,

247
00:16:31,700 --> 00:16:34,260
and that's all you have to say about him?

248
00:16:34,920 --> 00:16:38,120
It's obvious neither of you knows the first thing about him.

249
00:16:38,860 --> 00:16:41,320
I've come here because I need your help.

250
00:16:42,040 --> 00:16:44,740
My friend Richard has already died at his hands.

251
00:16:45,340 --> 00:16:49,200
Right now, as we speak, a man named Tenma is...

252
00:16:49,200 --> 00:16:52,120
He's moving toward something drastic that can't be undone.

253
00:16:53,560 --> 00:16:55,360
Please, you have to help me.

254
00:16:57,360 --> 00:17:04,800
No, more importantly, you'll end up like all the other couples mentioned in this report.

255
00:17:05,400 --> 00:17:08,660
They were all previous foster parents of Johan's just like you.

256
00:17:09,480 --> 00:17:11,060
Murdered every one of them.

257
00:17:13,500 --> 00:17:16,720
You have to leave now. If you stay, you'll die.

258
00:17:39,700 --> 00:17:42,840
Oh, the apple tree bore such small fruit.

259
00:17:43,740 --> 00:17:47,520
Uh-huh. But I think next year's apples will be much healthier.

260
00:17:48,120 --> 00:17:49,600
That will be delightful.

261
00:17:50,380 --> 00:17:53,720
Yes. So very delightful.

262
00:17:54,740 --> 00:17:57,500
He's going to be killed by a Japanese guy soon.

263
00:17:58,240 --> 00:18:00,320
Is that what Johan is telling those kids?

264
00:18:01,120 --> 00:18:03,880
Correct. What do you think? What's it mean?

265
00:18:05,620 --> 00:18:08,820
Well, he's not thinking about suicide, that's for sure.

266
00:18:09,120 --> 00:18:11,160
Okay, but what does it mean?

267
00:18:11,480 --> 00:18:15,560
Man, who really knows what goes on in a brilliant mind like that.

268
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:19,680
Although, I can at least say this much.

269
00:18:19,680 --> 00:18:25,280
If nuclear war broke out and the world burned to ash, he'd still be standing.

270
00:18:38,900 --> 00:18:42,080
He's basically telling us that there's nothing we can do.

271
00:18:43,040 --> 00:18:47,340
And he's right. Everything we've done so far has led us absolutely nowhere.

272
00:18:47,340 --> 00:18:50,540
My God, we weren't even able to save poor Richard.

273
00:18:51,220 --> 00:18:53,120
Look, we can't just throw in the towel.

274
00:18:53,260 --> 00:18:56,240
But we still haven't been able to track down Dr. Tenma.

275
00:18:56,740 --> 00:19:00,780
Aw, face it, we couldn't stop him from trying to kill Johan even if we wanted to.

276
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:01,900
It's been in vain!

277
00:19:02,240 --> 00:19:05,820
Dr. Reichwein, please! We need to try and remain calm here.

278
00:19:06,720 --> 00:19:08,060
Yeah, you're right.

279
00:19:13,360 --> 00:19:16,260
He talked about breaking up the line of ants.

280
00:19:19,040 --> 00:19:21,960
Even ants possess souls.

281
00:19:26,100 --> 00:19:27,600
Doctor, where are you going?

282
00:19:28,300 --> 00:19:31,780
At this point, we've got nothing to lose, do we?

283
00:19:32,720 --> 00:19:33,160
Huh?

284
00:19:34,060 --> 00:19:36,700
It's time to tell the old man our story.

285
00:19:37,560 --> 00:19:40,160
I'm going to have a little talk with Shuvald.

286
00:19:42,780 --> 00:19:45,120
What? An additional 50 chairs?

287
00:19:45,120 --> 00:19:48,660
So many people. This list just keeps growing and growing.

288
00:19:49,040 --> 00:19:52,900
You mean all of this is just for Mr. Shuvalt's book donation ceremony?

289
00:19:53,200 --> 00:19:57,180
Yeah. A lot of VIPs have been added. It's turning into a pretty big thing.

290
00:19:57,720 --> 00:20:01,060
I guess everything Shuvalt does is bound to turn into an event.

291
00:20:10,080 --> 00:20:12,660
The library will be closing shortly.

292
00:20:12,660 --> 00:20:17,340
Again, the library will be closing shortly.

293
00:20:42,740 --> 00:20:43,820
Excuse me.

294
00:20:45,740 --> 00:20:49,600
I'm sorry, but could you get that book down for me?

295
00:20:50,360 --> 00:20:54,220
It's that Czech dictionary up on the top. I can't reach it.

296
00:20:55,960 --> 00:20:58,500
Oh, okay. Is this it?

297
00:21:00,620 --> 00:21:03,660
Yes. I'm sorry. Thanks a lot.

298
00:21:03,980 --> 00:21:04,420
Sure.

299
00:21:04,980 --> 00:21:07,000
Actually, I'm borrowing a Czech picture book.

300
00:21:07,320 --> 00:21:08,580
I'm trying to translate it.

301
00:21:09,220 --> 00:21:10,140
I see.

302
00:21:10,140 --> 00:21:12,560
Would you believe it?

303
00:21:13,040 --> 00:21:16,380
My friend collapsed right here out of nowhere while looking at this book.

304
00:21:16,920 --> 00:21:17,440
Oh.

305
00:21:17,660 --> 00:21:21,840
I thought that maybe there was something in the book that could have triggered that response.

306
00:21:23,380 --> 00:21:25,960
So your friend, he's alright now?

307
00:21:26,060 --> 00:21:28,820
Yeah, he's fine. Thanks again.

308
00:21:29,200 --> 00:21:29,720
Sure.

309
00:21:41,380 --> 00:21:42,490
Let's see...

310
00:21:42,860 --> 00:21:46,140
Once upon a time in a land far away...

311
00:21:49,840 --> 00:21:53,460
There lived a nameless monster.

312
00:21:55,360 --> 00:21:57,720
He was dying to have a name.

313
00:21:59,180 --> 00:22:01,500
So the monster...

314
00:22:02,140 --> 00:22:06,980
So the monster made up his mind to set out on a journey to look for one.

315
00:22:10,140 --> 00:22:12,100
Huh. Weird book.

316
00:22:12,880 --> 00:22:14,000
We're closing up, hon.

317
00:22:14,440 --> 00:22:14,900
'Kay.

318
00:22:16,300 --> 00:22:18,660
And we'll be closed tomorrow for the ceremony.

319
00:22:54,080 --> 00:22:55,480
[MUSIC]

320
00:23:28,140 --> 00:23:29,540
[MUSIC]

321
00:23:40,160 --> 00:23:41,640
